DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Ongoing event<br>Campus location: Gowen Hall
  (GWN)<br>Campus room: Tateuchi East Asia Library\, George M. Beckmann R
 eading Room (Gowen 3rd)<br>Accessibility Contact: hkyi@uw.edu<br>Event T
 ypes: Exhibits<br>Event sponsors: Tateuchi East Asia Library<br><br><p><
 strong><a href="https://lib.uw.edu/location/tateuchi-east-asia-library/"
  target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Tateuchi East Asia Library</a> at th
 e University of Washington&#160\;</strong>invites the public to visit <e
 m>Reimagining Korean Jogakbo: From Tradition to Sustainability</em>\, on
  view April 6&#8211\;30\, 2026\, in the Reading Room exhibit cases at th
 e Tateuchi Library\, featuring works by Bella Youngok Kim.&#160\;<br><br
 ><br><strong>Reimagining Korean <em>Jogakbo</em>: From Tradition to Sust
 ainability</strong> introduces <em>Jogakbo</em>\, a traditional Korean w
 rapping cloth made from small fabric remnants. Created by women in the h
 ousehold\, <em>Jogakbo</em> reflects resourcefulness\, care\, and the be
 auty of everyday materials.</p><p><br>Inspired by this tradition\, Bella
  Yongok Kim reinterprets <em>Jogakbo</em> through contemporary art using
  recycled plastic packaging and fabric. By stitching together discarded 
 materials\, she transforms what was once overlooked into new patterns an
 d forms.</p><p><br>Through this exhibition\, visitors can explore the hi
 storical roots of <em>Jogakbo</em> and its connection to sustainability
 \, while discovering how traditional ideas continue to inspire contempora
 ry artistic practice.<br><br><strong>**Meet the artist on opening day Mo
 nday April 6 from 4&#8211\;5 p.m. for questions and a brief coversation&
 #160\;of her exhibit.**</strong><br>&#160\;</p><p><strong>Artist Bio</st
 rong></p><p><strong>Bella Yongok Kim</strong> is a mixed media and fiber
  artist based in Gig Harbor\, Washington. Born and raised in Korea\, she
  studied fiber art and design at Ewha Womans University. Her work is ins
 pired by Korean textile traditions\, especially Jogakbo\, and explores t
 hemes of sustainability\, memory\, and transformation.<br>&#160\;</p><p>
 Kim creates artworks using recycled materials such as plastic packaging 
 and fabric scraps\, stitching them together with a sewing machine to for
 m new patterns and textures. She has exhibited widely\, including at the
  Bainbridge Island Museum of Art\, Whatcom Museum\, the Northwest Quilt 
 &amp\; Fiber Art Museum\, and the Cheongju International Craft Biennale 
 in Korea. Kim is a recipient of the Artist Trust GAP Award\, recognition
  from the Korean American Coalition\, and her work is held in the Burke 
 Museum collection.<br><br>Through her practice\, she invites viewers to 
 reconsider the value of everyday materials and the creative possibilitie
 s of reuse.&#160\;<br>&#160\;</p><p>For more info is available at <a hre
 f="https://www.bellakim.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Bellakim.co
 m</a></p>
CATEGORIES:Outside the School
