X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:UW Af
 rican Studies Program<br>UW American Ethnic Studies
DTSTAMP:20260311T114347Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event<br>Online Meeting Link: htt
 ps://washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/tFVftGpFSHakAb2JlDqxkA<br>Acces
 sibility Contact: sameerai@uw.edu<br>Event Types: Lectures/Seminars<br>E
 vent sponsors: UW African Studies Program\nUW American Ethnic Studies<br
 ><br>Free and open to the public. <a href="https://washington.zoom.us/me
 eting/register/tFVftGpFSHakAb2JlDqxkA" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Re
 gistration required.</a><br><br>Studying Black feminist impulses\, schol
 ars of Women\, Gender\, and Sexuality Studies have long explored the pro
 to-Black Feminist impulses in Phillis Wheatley&#39\;s poetry\, Harriet T
 ubman&#39\;s activism\, and Sojourner Truth&#39\;s lectures. Yet African
  and African descendant women have navigated the crossroads of race\, ge
 nder\, and justice long before the 18th century. This talk traces Black 
 Feminist Thought back to the early modern Atlantic. The first recorded B
 lack woman of the Americas is a shadowy figure known only as La Negra de
 l Hospital\, or the Black woman of the hospital. She established the fir
 st colonial-era public healing site in the island colony of Santo Doming
 o before the first enslaved Africans arrived in the hemisphere in 1502. 
 Before Black Feminisms\, La Negra was interrupting injustice through her
  care work and women-conscious healing in an Indigenous stronghold\, act
 ively resisting the Spanish conquest. By studying La Negra del Hospital
 \, this talk will model how Black Feminist methods mend the fragmented ar
 chive of transatlantic slavery to show this pioneering Black woman&#39\;
 s contributions to Black Feminist Thought.<br><br>Sophia Monegro is a li
 terary scholar working at the crossroads of Black Women&#8217\;s Intelle
 ctual History\, Dominican Studies\, and Digital Humanities. She earned h
 er PhD in the African and African Diaspora Studies Department at The Uni
 versity of Texas at Austin in 2025. Currently\, Dr. Monegro serves as th
 e inaugural Postdoctoral Fellow at the Center for the Study of Race\, Et
 hnicity\, and Equity at Washington University in St. Louis.&#160\;Starti
 ng this July\, Dr. Monegro will join the faculty at Smith College as a t
 enure-track Assistant Professor in Africana Studies. Her research\, feat
 ured in&#160\;Oxford Bibliographies in Latino Studies&#160\;and the&#160
 \;Global Black Thought&#160\;Journal\, excavates Black Feminist thought 
 and African descendant women&#8217\;s activism in colonial Santo Domingo
 .&#160\;The Fulbright Program\, Mellon Foundation\, and American Associa
 tion of University Women have supported her research.&#160\;As a digital
  humanist\, Monegro&#8217\;s digital projects democratize access to arch
 ives that account for Black Caribbean women&#8217\;s intellectualism in 
 the Atlantic world.&#160\;She is the Primary Investigator on an ACLS Dig
 ital Justice Seed Grant for the creation of &#8220\;Cimarronas: A Black 
 Women&#8217\;s Archive of Ayiti-Quisqueya\,&#8221\; a trilingual digital
  platform that makes Black Caribbean women&#8217\;s histories accessible
  to diverse audiences.<br><br>The Global Africa Transcontinental Seminar
  brings together UW African Studies\, the Department of History at Cheik
 h Anta Diop University in Dakar\, Senegal\, and the African Program at S
 ciences Po Paris\, France\, and aims to engage scholars and students aro
 und contemporary research on &#8220\;African Worlds&#8221\; or &#8221\;G
 lobal Africa.&#8221\; The virtual monthly lectures and discussions will 
 connect communities of scholars across the humanities and social science
 s in North America\, Africa\, and Europe to discuss themes such as Black
  radical politics\, decolonial feminisms\, African technologies\, enviro
 nmental history\, postcolonial migration\, religion and modernity\, and 
 language. Through consideration of the ways in which the three continent
 s have influenced each other and their respective institutional contexts
 \, the seminar will bring original and situated perspectives on a range 
 of topics and further a rich conversation across institutions\, teaching
  traditions\, and research.
CATEGORIES:Outside the School
