DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event<br>Campus location: Kane Ha
 ll (KNE)<br>Campus room: Kane 225\, Walker-Ames Room<br>Accessibility Co
 ntact: jewishst@uw.edu<br>Event Types: Academics<br>Event sponsors: Stro
 um Center for Jewish Studies<br>Target Audience: Open to public. Registr
 ation required.<br><br>Join us for the first lecture of the UW&#39\;s an
 nual Stroum Lectures in Jewish Studies. This year the series features Un
 iversity of Michigan scholar and artist <strong>Rafael Neis.&#160\;</str
 ong><br><br><strong><em><a href="https://events.uw.edu/event/590afaea-37
 91-49a3-82c8-0c6e67964905/summary?tm=Q9gammsmKW9RQo88byzNfSMaGMgXid85zxw
 7FUuji4M" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Register Here</a>. Registration
  Required.&#160\;</em></strong><br><br><strong>Lecture 1:&#160\;Did &#82
 16\;Men&#8217\; and &#8216\;Women&#8217\; Always Exist? What the Talmud 
 Can Tell Us</strong><br>We often assume that the categories &#8220\;man&
 #8221\; and &#8220\;woman&#8221\; are timeless and self-evident. But wha
 t if they aren&#8217\;t?&#160\;In this talk\, Professor Rafael Neis invi
 tes us to explore a surprising question: did &#8220\;men&#8221\; and &#8
 220\;women\,&#8221\; as fixed and stable categories\, always exist in th
 e way we imagine them today?&#160\;Turning to the Talmud\, Neis shows ho
 w the rabbis wrestled with bodies\, identity\, and social roles in ways 
 that don&#8217\;t always fit neatly into modern assumptions. By setting 
 aside what we think we already know about gender\, we can discover fresh
  and unexpected ways of reading these ancient texts&#8212\;and gain insi
 ght into how the rabbis themselves understood human difference.&#160\;Al
 ong the way\, Neis opens up intriguing new perspectives on rabbinic thou
 ght\, revealing a tradition that is more curious\, complex\, and inventi
 ve than we might expect.&#160\;Please join us for an informal reception 
 following the lecture.<br><br><strong>Read about the <a href="https://ca
 lendar.washington.edu/sea_jewish/Stroum-Lectures-2026-with-Rafael-Neis-M
 onsters-Hybrids-and-Holy-Images-Rethinking-Bodies-in-Ancient-Jewish-Art/
 E196384221" target="_blank" rel="noopener">second lecture here.</a></str
 ong><br><br><strong>Rafael&#160\;Neis</strong>&#160\;is a scholar and ar
 tist. Neis is the Jean and Samuel Frankel Professor of Rabbinic Literatu
 re and is appointed in the Department of History and Frankel Center for 
 Judaic Studies at the University of Michigan. As Faculty Director of Art
 s Learning at Michigan&#8217\;s&#160\;Arts initiative\, Neis supports ca
 mpus-wide art-integrated pedagogy. Their second book\,&#160\;<em>When&#1
 60\;a Human Gives Birth to a Raven: Rabbis &amp\; the Reproduction of Sp
 ecies</em>\, was published in 2023 by University of California Press. Th
 eir artwork has been featured in shows and in many publications.&#160\;<
 br><br>---<br><em><strong>The&#160\;Stroum Lectures in Jewish Studies</s
 trong>&#160\;is a nationally-renowned series of public lectures\, which 
 has brought Jewish studies luminaries from around the globe to the Unive
 rsity of Washington for more than fifty years. Made possible through the
  support of the Samuel and Althea Stroum Lectures Endowment\, this annua
 l series is a cornerstone program of UW&#39\;s Stroum Center for Jewish 
 Studies and has led to impactful conversations\, groundbreaking scholars
 hip\, and award-winning publications. You may view the full Stroum Lectu
 res archive&#160\;<a href="https://jewishstudies.washington.edu/stroum-l
 ectures-archive-2/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>&#160\;and re
 view corresponding books published by University of Washington Press&#16
 0\;<a href="https://uwapress.uw.edu/search-results/?series=samuel-and-al
 thea-stroum-lectures-in-jewish-studies" target="_blank" rel="noopener">h
 ere</a>.<br><br>Image: 4th-7th c. incantation bowl written in Aramaic fr
 om Iraq. Photo by Osama Shukir Muhammed Amin via Wikimedia Commons.</em>
 
CATEGORIES:Outside the School
