DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event<br>Campus location: Student
  Union Building (HUB)<br>Campus room: HUB 214<br>Accessibility Contact: 
 jewishst@uw.edu<br>Event Types: Academics<br>Event sponsors: The Stroum 
 Center for Jewish Studies<br>Target Audience: Open to public. Registrati
 on required.<br><br>Join us for the first lecture of UW&#39\;s annual St
 roum Lectures in Jewish Studies. This year the series features Universit
 y of Michigan scholar and artist <strong>Rafael Neis.&#160\;</strong><br
 ><br><em>Registration link coming soon. </em><strong>Read about the <a h
 ref="https://calendar.washington.edu/sea_jewish/Stroum-Lectures-2026-wit
 h-Rafael-Neis-Did-Men-and-Women-Always-Exist-What-the-Talmud-Can-Tell-Us
 /E196383949" target="_blank" rel="noopener">first lecture here.</a>&#160
 \;</strong><br><br><strong>Lecture 2. Monsters\, Hybrids\, and Holy Imag
 es: Rethinking Bodies in Ancient Jewish Art&#160\;&#160\;</strong><br>Wa
 lk through the ancient world and you would have been surrounded by image
 s of all kinds of beings&#8212\;human figures\, animals\, hybrids\, and 
 creatures that blur the line between the familiar and the fantastic. The
 se images appeared everywhere: in streets and homes\, bathhouses and syn
 agogues\, public buildings and sacred spaces.&#160\;In this talk\, Profe
 ssor Rafael Neis explores a handful of striking examples from ancient Je
 wish art and asks what happens when we look at them with fresh eyes. Ins
 tead of sorting these figures into modern boxes about &#8220\;human\,&#8
 221\; &#8220\;animal\,&#8221\; &#8220\;male\,&#8221\; or &#8220\;female
 \,&#8221\; Neis invites us to step back and see how ancient artists and c
 ommunities imagined bodies more broadly.&#160\;By letting go of some of 
 our present-day assumptions\, we begin to notice new patterns and possib
 ilities&#8212\;and gain insight into how people in the ancient world und
 erstood identity\, difference\, and the sacred. The result is a richer\,
  more surprising picture of Jewish visual culture\, filled with creativi
 ty\, complexity\, and imagination.&#160\;<br><br><strong>Rafael&#160\;Ne
 is</strong>&#160\;is a scholar and artist. Neis is the Jean and Samuel F
 rankel Professor of Rabbinic Literature and is appointed in the Departme
 nt of History and Frankel Center for Judaic Studies at the University of
  Michigan. As Faculty Director of Arts Learning at Michigan&#8217\;s&#16
 0\;Arts initiative\, Neis supports campus-wide art-integrated pedagogy. 
 Their second book\,&#160\;<em>When&#160\;a Human Gives Birth to a Raven:
  Rabbis &amp\; the Reproduction of Species</em>\, was published in 2023 
 by University of California Press. Their artwork has been featured in sh
 ows and in many publications.&#160\;<br><br>---<br><em>The&#160\;<strong
 >Stroum Lectures in Jewish Studies</strong>&#160\;is a nationally-renown
 ed series of public lectures\, which has brought Jewish studies luminari
 es from around the globe to the University of Washington for more than f
 ifty years. Made possible through the support of the Samuel and Althea S
 troum Lectures Endowment\, this annual series is a cornerstone program o
 f UW&#39\;s Stroum Center for Jewish Studies and has led to impactful co
 nversations\, groundbreaking scholarship\, and award-winning publication
 s. You may view the full Stroum Lectures archive&#160\;<a href="https://
 jewishstudies.washington.edu/stroum-lectures-archive-2/" target="_blank"
  rel="noopener">here</a>&#160\;and review corresponding books published 
 by University of Washington Press&#160\;<a href="https://uwapress.uw.edu
 /search-results/?series=samuel-and-althea-stroum-lectures-in-jewish-stud
 ies" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>.<br><br>Image:&#160\;4th-7t
 h c. incantation bowl written in Aramaic from Iraq. Photo by Osama Shuki
 r Muhammed Amin via Wikimedia Commons.</em>
CATEGORIES:Outside the School
